and limited edition serigraphs.

00:34:57.925 --> 00:35:00.050
ERIK HALL: Absolutely, and
thanks for the question.

00:35:00.050 --> 00:35:03.250
There is a definite distinction
and, in fact, the art market

00:35:03.250 --> 00:35:06.780
now is-- the last
stat I saw on it

00:35:06.780 --> 00:35:09.290
was that 3% of the
art market is actually

00:35:09.290 --> 00:35:11.220
being driven by
the print business,

00:35:11.220 --> 00:35:13.870
and that print business is
actually very limited edition

00:35:13.870 --> 00:35:15.940
lithographs.

00:35:15.940 --> 00:35:18.100
There's a fancy word
out there called giclee,

00:35:18.100 --> 00:35:20.580
and that's just a made up
word, and people, galleries

00:35:20.580 --> 00:35:22.340
will toss that word
out there it's just

00:35:22.340 --> 00:35:25.720
a fancy word that was made
up in the '70s for four color

00:35:25.720 --> 00:35:26.590
printing.

00:35:26.590 --> 00:35:29.690
That's the kind of stuff that
I want people to kind of like

00:35:29.690 --> 00:35:32.370
understand and know that there's
really not a whole lot of value

00:35:32.370 --> 00:35:33.070
in that.

00:35:33.070 --> 00:35:36.360
Lithograph runs signed by
an authorized print house,

00:35:36.360 --> 00:35:39.030
by an artist, have a
great deal of value.

00:35:39.030 --> 00:35:40.820
They trade on the open market.

00:35:40.820 --> 00:35:42.600
And, like I said,
they drive about 3%

00:35:42.600 --> 00:35:44.680
of the art market,
the auction market,

00:35:44.680 --> 00:35:46.430
so if you do any
kind of research,

00:35:46.430 --> 00:35:49.030
you will see that there's
Warhol's and there are still

00:35:49.030 --> 00:35:52.880
Picasso's trading out there that
were from the authorized houses

00:35:52.880 --> 00:35:57.410
that were signed, numbered, and
they have the stamp and seal

00:35:57.410 --> 00:35:59.147
of the authorized print house.

00:35:59.147 --> 00:36:00.730
So the more you
understand about that,

00:36:00.730 --> 00:36:03.021
the more that distinction
actually becomes quite clear.

00:36:03.021 --> 00:36:04.970
Yes, thank you, there
is a definite difference

00:36:04.970 --> 00:36:06.410
between the two.

00:36:06.410 --> 00:36:10.700
AUDIENCE: But there
are artists who

00:36:10.700 --> 00:36:17.390
work in giclee as a medium and
have limited edition, signed

00:36:17.390 --> 00:36:17.959
runs.

00:36:17.959 --> 00:36:18.750
ERIK HALL: They do.

00:36:18.750 --> 00:36:19.490
That's true.

00:36:19.490 --> 00:36:19.630
AUDIENCE: Giclees.

00:36:19.630 --> 00:36:20.255
CLIFF: They do.

00:36:20.255 --> 00:36:21.110
That's true.

00:36:21.110 --> 00:36:23.110
Let me be clear that the
artist doesn't actually

00:36:23.110 --> 00:36:24.009
work in giclee.

00:36:24.009 --> 00:36:24.800
That's not a thing.

00:36:24.800 --> 00:36:27.939
That's four-color printing.

00:36:27.939 --> 00:36:30.480
So what I'm referring to is the
difference between a painting

00:36:30.480 --> 00:36:32.400
that may be-- and
what I'm encouraging,

00:36:32.400 --> 00:36:37.400
really, is that if say a giclee
print is 500 bucks that you

00:36:37.400 --> 00:36:39.250
take that 500 bucks,
instead of buying

00:36:39.250 --> 00:36:43.580
that that mass-produced print,
that you go to visit, say,

00:36:43.580 --> 00:36:45.167
an artist's studio
and find something

00:36:45.167 --> 00:36:46.250
that hits you really well.

00:36:46.250 --> 00:36:49.184
AUDIENCE: Not all giclees
are mass produced.

00:36:55.110 --> 00:37:00.130
I understand that it's
a technological process,

00:37:00.130 --> 00:37:03.250
but there are artists
who I consider

00:37:03.250 --> 00:37:07.570
fine artists who work
in a digital medium,

00:37:07.570 --> 00:37:15.960
and they physical output of
it is a limited edition giclee

00:37:15.960 --> 00:37:18.442
that might only be 100 copies.

00:37:18.442 --> 00:37:19.150
ERIK HALL: Right.

00:37:19.150 --> 00:37:20.532
AUDIENCE: And they
sign each one.

00:37:20.532 --> 00:37:21.240
ERIK HALL: Right.

00:37:21.240 --> 00:37:22.915
AUDIENCE: So just
the fact that it's

00:37:22.915 --> 00:37:25.810
a giclee as opposed to
a lithograph, I think,

00:37:25.810 --> 00:37:28.574
is not important.

00:37:28.574 --> 00:37:29.990
ERIK HALL: Right
and, to be clear,

00:37:29.990 --> 00:37:31.823
I'm not saying that
giclees are a bad thing.

00:37:31.823 --> 00:37:34.890
I've actually reproduced my
own work for a friend of mine

00:37:34.890 --> 00:37:36.374
on a certain occasion.

00:37:36.374 --> 00:37:38.290
They couldn't afford an
original piece of art.

00:37:38.290 --> 00:37:40.890
I desperately wanted them
to have a piece of my work,

00:37:40.890 --> 00:37:43.190
because they were in a
crisis in their own life,

00:37:43.190 --> 00:37:46.230
and I thought that that would
be uplifting thing for them.

00:37:46.230 --> 00:37:47.634
And so I did have one done.

00:37:47.634 --> 00:37:48.550
They called it giclee.

00:37:48.550 --> 00:37:51.040
It's just four-color printing.

00:37:51.040 --> 00:37:54.124
Lithographs are done in much
larger runs than giclees even.

00:37:54.124 --> 00:37:55.540
Giclees you can
do in anything you

00:37:55.540 --> 00:37:57.830
want, because of the
type of print that it is.

00:37:57.830 --> 00:38:00.510
Having said that, I'm not
really specifically talking

00:38:00.510 --> 00:38:05.170
about the type, whether it's a
lithograph, serigraph, giclee.

00:38:05.170 --> 00:38:08.390
Moreover I'm talking about the
volume that it's produced in

00:38:08.390 --> 00:38:10.350
and whether that
volume was produced

00:38:10.350 --> 00:38:12.800
by an authorized house.

00:38:12.800 --> 00:38:16.290
So the distinction there
just lies in the rights.

00:38:16.290 --> 00:38:18.920
Who has the right to do it
and how much were allotted,

00:38:18.920 --> 00:38:20.900
and were those done well.

00:38:20.900 --> 00:38:23.880
A reputable printing house is
going to do really great job.

00:38:23.880 --> 00:38:26.330
The physical manifestation
of digital art

00:38:26.330 --> 00:38:28.850
is something that we're going
to contend with more and more,

00:38:28.850 --> 00:38:31.040
and I think that there's
a great market for it

00:38:31.040 --> 00:38:32.720
as long as it's
done in limited runs

00:38:32.720 --> 00:38:35.810
so that the product
itself isn't diluted.

00:38:35.810 --> 00:38:37.360
That's all I'm saying.

00:38:37.360 --> 00:38:37.974
Thank you.

00:38:37.974 --> 00:38:40.390
CLIFF: And I think that raises
an interesting question too

00:38:40.390 --> 00:38:42.130
in the photography space.

00:38:42.130 --> 00:38:44.130
You have the large
prints, you'll

00:38:44.130 --> 00:38:46.490
change it to black and white
or do a certain crop of it

00:38:46.490 --> 00:38:50.040
and then sell it as
a completely new run.

00:38:50.040 --> 00:38:52.950
ERIK HALL: So what artists
do with the reproduction

00:38:52.950 --> 00:38:56.420
of their own work, I think, is
part of the artistic process,

00:38:56.420 --> 00:38:59.290
and I would never hold
that against anyone.

00:38:59.290 --> 00:39:02.050
All I'm saying is that I
would encourage someone,

00:39:02.050 --> 00:39:05.220
that if they wanted to buy
an original piece of artwork

00:39:05.220 --> 00:39:08.030
to educate themselves and
make sure that this is truly

00:39:08.030 --> 00:39:09.770
at original piece of artwork.

00:39:09.770 --> 00:39:12.820
If it's a physical manifestation
of a digital print, then

00:39:12.820 --> 00:39:14.770
that's the original
form that was

00:39:14.770 --> 00:39:19.600
presented to the public and,
as such, that's original work.

00:39:19.600 --> 00:39:22.490
But when you go to a place
like Bed, Bath and Beyond

00:39:22.490 --> 00:39:25.020
or some other place,
it becomes less art,

00:39:25.020 --> 00:39:26.750
it becomes decoration,
and I'm simply

00:39:26.750 --> 00:39:29.110
just trying to get people
to avoid decoration

00:39:29.110 --> 00:39:30.144
in favor of art.

00:39:30.144 --> 00:39:32.060
AUDIENCE: I don't really
know how to ask this.

00:39:32.060 --> 00:39:35.610
I'm sort of stuck on this
idea of art versus decoration.

00:39:35.610 --> 00:39:42.130
Like, why does it make sense
to put art in people's homes?

00:39:42.130 --> 00:39:43.600
Like that is decoration.

00:39:43.600 --> 00:39:49.900
It's kind of a weird-- to me,
it's kind of a weird way for us

00:39:49.900 --> 00:39:52.910
as a society to be
valuing art as to have it

00:39:52.910 --> 00:39:56.100
on the wall in your house
or something, like just you,

00:39:56.100 --> 00:39:56.890
one person?

00:39:56.890 --> 00:40:00.910
I don't know-- I feel
like that actually

00:40:00.910 --> 00:40:03.640
is a good place for
decoration, because it's just

00:40:03.640 --> 00:40:05.910
like furnishing your room.

00:40:05.910 --> 00:40:08.110
ERIK HALL: I think I touched
on it-- first of all,

00:40:08.110 --> 00:40:10.600
thank you for the question.

00:40:10.600 --> 00:40:13.520
As I understand
it, you're asking

00:40:13.520 --> 00:40:17.530
why isn't a home a good
place for decoration

00:40:17.530 --> 00:40:21.160
and the difference between art
and decoration in that regard?

00:40:24.275 --> 00:40:26.110
AUDIENCE: Yeah,
maybe the other way.

00:40:26.110 --> 00:40:28.790
Like why is a home a
good place for art?

00:40:28.790 --> 00:40:31.332
ERIK HALL: I think the home
is the best place for art.

00:40:31.332 --> 00:40:32.280
AUDIENCE: Why?

00:40:32.280 --> 00:40:34.240
ERIK HALL: For me
specifically, and that's

00:40:34.240 --> 00:40:37.490
the only way I can talk about
it, to go with what I know

00:40:37.490 --> 00:40:41.410
about it, and every piece that's
in our home has meaning to us,

00:40:41.410 --> 00:40:44.780
and it surpasses the
monetary value of the piece.

00:40:44.780 --> 00:40:47.407
It has something
poignant about it

00:40:47.407 --> 00:40:48.990
that speaks to
something that happened

00:40:48.990 --> 00:40:53.160
in our life or a relationship
we had with an artist.

00:40:53.160 --> 00:40:56.400
Just recently we
purchased a piece

00:40:56.400 --> 00:40:59.810
from an artist that
was really, really

00:40:59.810 --> 00:41:01.370
special to us, Cheryl Engstrom.

00:41:01.370 --> 00:41:03.943
A sculpture piece titled
"The Paris Wheel."

00:41:03.943 --> 00:41:06.100
It's a found object wheel.

00:41:06.100 --> 00:41:08.920
It's got letter openers
that were made out

00:41:08.920 --> 00:41:13.039
of bronze as the people
riding the wheel,

00:41:13.039 --> 00:41:14.080
and it's a pivotal piece.

00:41:14.080 --> 00:41:15.840
And it became even
more pivotal to us,

00:41:15.840 --> 00:41:18.100
because Cheryl passed
away four days ago,

00:41:18.100 --> 00:41:25.420
and so the home is a good
place for decoration, sure,

00:41:25.420 --> 00:41:30.430
but the art that you place in
there to decorate your home,

00:41:30.430 --> 00:41:35.160
it needs, in my opinion,
to speak to you at a higher

00:41:35.160 --> 00:41:39.030
level than something that you
said, oh, that looks nice,

00:41:39.030 --> 00:41:40.780
as you were passing
the decorative pillows

00:41:40.780 --> 00:41:41.737
section of the store.

00:41:41.737 --> 00:41:44.320
Like something that has meaning
to you, that's a deep meaning,

00:41:44.320 --> 00:41:45.736
and I'm not saying
that that needs

00:41:45.736 --> 00:41:48.920
to be something that came
from a gallery or a museum.

00:41:48.920 --> 00:41:52.050
That can simply be something
that you saw after you just

00:41:52.050 --> 00:41:54.350
had a heart-wrenching
moment that was laying

00:41:54.350 --> 00:41:56.404
by the side a street, a stick.

00:41:56.404 --> 00:41:58.445
Put it up in your house,
decorate it in some way,

00:41:58.445 --> 00:42:00.944
and when you look at it, let
it remind you of something that

00:42:00.944 --> 00:42:02.230
was important to you.

00:42:02.230 --> 00:42:03.530
That's all I'm saying.

00:42:03.530 --> 00:42:07.950
Just please try not
to equate those things

00:42:07.950 --> 00:42:10.231
that you see in a store
next to decorative pillows

00:42:10.231 --> 00:42:12.730
or glasses as something that's
going to be meaningful to you

00:42:12.730 --> 00:42:13.396
in the long run.

00:42:13.396 --> 00:42:14.710
That's decoration.

00:42:14.710 --> 00:42:16.920
That stick, in my
opinion, because it

00:42:16.920 --> 00:42:22.400
has a value that's bigger
than the cost, is now art.

00:42:22.400 --> 00:42:23.928
Does that make sense?

00:42:23.928 --> 00:42:26.210
AUDIENCE: Yeah.

00:42:26.210 --> 00:42:30.000
CLIFF: And also it
is a question, should

00:42:30.000 --> 00:42:33.290
the art be publicly on display?

00:42:33.290 --> 00:42:37.260
Are you preventing
people from seeing it

00:42:37.260 --> 00:42:40.370
by it being in your
house, just taking away--

00:42:40.370 --> 00:42:43.140
many great works of art
are in private collections,

00:42:43.140 --> 00:42:45.600
much to the consternation of
the people that go to museums.

00:42:45.600 --> 00:42:46.340
ERIK HALL: Right.

00:42:46.340 --> 00:42:49.796
That's a question that comes
up a lot in our industry,

00:42:49.796 --> 00:42:52.340
and there's a lot of dialogue
going back and forth on it.

00:42:52.340 --> 00:42:54.600
I am a subscriber,
and I firmly believe,

00:42:54.600 --> 00:42:58.230
like many in our industry
do, that artwork is borrowed.

00:42:58.230 --> 00:42:59.430
You don't own it.

00:42:59.430 --> 00:43:01.320
You rent it almost.

00:43:01.320 --> 00:43:04.490
You pay for it, you have
it, but you have a lifespan

00:43:04.490 --> 00:43:07.170
that pales in comparison
to a piece of art,

00:43:07.170 --> 00:43:10.870
and that's why art winds up in
museums or in estates that's

00:43:10.870 --> 00:43:13.980
passed on through families
and eventually winds up,

00:43:13.980 --> 00:43:17.780
hopefully, taken care
of in a public space.

00:43:17.780 --> 00:43:22.430
But the reality of it is
that some pieces do go unseen

00:43:22.430 --> 00:43:25.170
for hundreds of
years, and that's

00:43:25.170 --> 00:43:28.480
why when a piece
does surface again,

00:43:28.480 --> 00:43:30.600
it becomes such a big
deal in our community.

00:43:30.600 --> 00:43:33.360
But I'm a firm
believer, and many of us

00:43:33.360 --> 00:43:35.490
are, that artwork
is simply borrowed.

00:43:35.490 --> 00:43:39.080
I know all of our artwork
will be eventually given

00:43:39.080 --> 00:43:42.500
to someone else, and I'm hoping
that we do well enough in life

00:43:42.500 --> 00:43:45.450
that we're able to
set up a public space

00:43:45.450 --> 00:43:48.950
for that collection to be
viewed, if for no other reason

00:43:48.950 --> 00:43:52.720
so that I can feel that someone
else might feel what I felt

00:43:52.720 --> 00:43:55.480
when we purchased that work.

00:43:55.480 --> 00:43:57.940
AUDIENCE: Do you think there's
such a thing as bad art?

00:43:57.940 --> 00:43:59.610
ERIK HALL: Definitely.

00:43:59.610 --> 00:44:01.867
AUDIENCE: What makes
something bad art?

00:44:01.867 --> 00:44:03.950
ERIK HALL: There's two
ways to answer that for me.

00:44:03.950 --> 00:44:05.790
One of them is the
technical aspect.

00:44:05.790 --> 00:44:07.445
I'm a painter myself,
so I look at art,

00:44:07.445 --> 00:44:09.060
and I'm very
discerning about it.

00:44:09.060 --> 00:44:11.760
I think it's a great question,
because understanding

00:44:11.760 --> 00:44:14.060
good from bad might
be the very thing that

00:44:14.060 --> 00:44:17.467
saves your investment if
you're buying as a commodity.

00:44:17.467 --> 00:44:19.550
So that's why I say don't
ever buy as a commodity,

00:44:19.550 --> 00:44:20.520
because you're safe.

00:44:20.520 --> 00:44:23.000
Even if it's a bad piece of
art, you like it, you love it,

00:44:23.000 --> 00:44:25.520
and therefore its
investment is safe.

00:44:25.520 --> 00:44:28.310
Having said that,
technically speaking--

00:44:28.310 --> 00:44:30.980
and I'm still learning to
look at, say, abstract art,

00:44:30.980 --> 00:44:32.920
for instance-- but I
can recognize things

00:44:32.920 --> 00:44:36.050
very specifically now
about abstract art that

00:44:36.050 --> 00:44:38.164
lets me know that
this is a new painter.

00:44:38.164 --> 00:44:39.580
And I'm not going
to say it's bad.

00:44:39.580 --> 00:44:41.954
I'm going to say it's new,
someone that needs to progress

00:44:41.954 --> 00:44:43.340
a little bit in their career.

00:44:43.340 --> 00:44:45.600
And part of the
gallery's role is

00:44:45.600 --> 00:44:48.130
to be a really great
filter for the public

00:44:48.130 --> 00:44:51.430
so that that trust can
be developed over time,

00:44:51.430 --> 00:44:53.140
where you know that
we've already vetted

00:44:53.140 --> 00:44:54.500
a lot of this art for you.

00:44:54.500 --> 00:44:57.249
You vetted us over time,
we vet the art constantly,

00:44:57.249 --> 00:44:58.790
and that way when
you come in and you

00:44:58.790 --> 00:45:01.920
have that visceral
response to something, then

00:45:01.920 --> 00:45:04.180
you know that it's safe.

00:45:04.180 --> 00:45:09.260
You could buy this, it's
been vetted through us.

00:45:09.260 --> 00:45:12.510
The world doesn't agree on this,
but we do, and if you trust us,

00:45:12.510 --> 00:45:14.154
that kind of helps
it out a little bit.

00:45:14.154 --> 00:45:16.570
But, technically speaking,
like with an abstract painting,

00:45:16.570 --> 00:45:17.820
there'll be muddy parts in it.

00:45:17.820 --> 00:45:20.590
And by muddy I mean where things
happened while the paint was

00:45:20.590 --> 00:45:22.590
wet, and it turned this
kind of brown color,

00:45:22.590 --> 00:45:26.210
and the composition
was kind of poor.

00:45:26.210 --> 00:45:31.410
I'm a big believer in the
rule of odds, paintings being

00:45:31.410 --> 00:45:34.610
dissected into thirds as
a way to present them,

00:45:34.610 --> 00:45:37.050
in a way that gives you a
center line when you look at it.

00:45:37.050 --> 00:45:38.600
There's a bunch
of little things.

00:45:38.600 --> 00:45:42.260
Sometimes, for me, it's just
the technical aspect of it.

00:45:42.260 --> 00:45:44.110
Painting can be
great, but I think

00:45:44.110 --> 00:45:46.810
if there was a painterly mark
in it that just didn't sit well

00:45:46.810 --> 00:45:49.110
with me, that to me is
going to make it bad,

00:45:49.110 --> 00:45:52.086
but bad is kind of a tough word.

00:45:52.086 --> 00:45:53.710
And most of the time
I come across what

00:45:53.710 --> 00:45:55.961
you're calling bad artwork,
it's just new artwork.

00:45:55.961 --> 00:45:57.960
Someone that needs to
develop a little bit more.

00:45:57.960 --> 00:46:00.680
We see it all the time, and
instead of telling people no,

00:46:00.680 --> 00:46:02.470
we always try to
take that opportunity

00:46:02.470 --> 00:46:04.080
to coach them up a little bit.

00:46:04.080 --> 00:46:06.740
Sometimes it's tough love,
but it helps them evolve.

00:46:06.740 --> 00:46:10.265
So eventually that bad
artist becomes really good.

00:46:10.265 --> 00:46:11.640
CLIFF: I had
another question too

00:46:11.640 --> 00:46:14.920
about the role of names
and supply and demand

00:46:14.920 --> 00:46:17.410
in the expanding internet age.

00:46:17.410 --> 00:46:19.040
You have dvnr.com.

00:46:19.040 --> 00:46:21.690
Anyone can throw
up a piece of art.

00:46:21.690 --> 00:46:24.200
They get the likes on
it and the popularity,

00:46:24.200 --> 00:46:26.850
but at the same time, if
you were to ask somebody

00:46:26.850 --> 00:46:29.300
on the street, name a
really great sculptor

00:46:29.300 --> 00:46:31.270
or visual artist
or glass artist,

00:46:31.270 --> 00:46:34.390
there's only a few names,
and it's a crowded space.

00:46:34.390 --> 00:46:36.940
How is that evolving
as the years go on?

00:46:36.940 --> 00:46:39.130
ERIK HALL: Well, first of
all, I love the internet

00:46:39.130 --> 00:46:41.300
as a medium to promote artwork.

00:46:41.300 --> 00:46:45.227
I think it's a really,
really tough occupation

00:46:45.227 --> 00:46:46.810
to exploit for a
living, first of all,

00:46:46.810 --> 00:46:49.390
for anyone that's in
it, on any level of it,

00:46:49.390 --> 00:46:52.310
and it favors the few.

00:46:52.310 --> 00:46:55.570
And so the people that rest
in the middle and the bottom

00:46:55.570 --> 00:46:57.470
are always kind
of scraping along.

00:46:57.470 --> 00:46:59.520
I mentioned earlier that
sometimes just staying

00:46:59.520 --> 00:47:01.290
in the business is
succeeding in the business,

00:47:01.290 --> 00:47:02.930
and that's kind of
what I mean by that.

00:47:02.930 --> 00:47:11.180
So the question of,
say, places like DVNR.

00:47:11.180 --> 00:47:13.710
Great landing spot
for people that can

00:47:13.710 --> 00:47:15.214
get an opinion on something.

00:47:15.214 --> 00:47:16.880
But those places are
really no different

00:47:16.880 --> 00:47:20.285
than any other platform
that we use to promote,

00:47:20.285 --> 00:47:21.160
even if it's not art.

00:47:21.160 --> 00:47:23.582
Whether it's ourself or
our vacation or our kid,

00:47:23.582 --> 00:47:25.290
you know, these are
all places for people

00:47:25.290 --> 00:47:27.180
to go and kind of
form an opinion.

00:47:27.180 --> 00:47:30.380
The more places you see
it, the better, the broader

00:47:30.380 --> 00:47:31.170
the audience gets.

00:47:31.170 --> 00:47:33.770
And I think for that reason
those platforms are really

00:47:33.770 --> 00:47:35.270
super successful,
and I personally

00:47:35.270 --> 00:47:37.186
don't have a problem
with them even though I'm

00:47:37.186 --> 00:47:38.640
in the business of selling art.

00:47:38.640 --> 00:47:41.670
I think that a broad
awareness of art in general,

00:47:41.670 --> 00:47:44.510
in all of its forms, is
really, really important

00:47:44.510 --> 00:47:47.520
and becoming kind
of a lifeline--

00:47:47.520 --> 00:47:50.236
a financial lifeline--
for many artists.

00:47:50.236 --> 00:47:51.860
You sell a few
paintings here and there

00:47:51.860 --> 00:47:54.304
and keep that studio rent paid.

00:47:54.304 --> 00:47:55.720
CLIFF: And how do
you guide people

00:47:55.720 --> 00:47:58.140
towards the lesser
known names, like things

00:47:58.140 --> 00:48:01.561
that aren't household names as
they walk into your gallery?

00:48:01.561 --> 00:48:03.060
ERIK HALL: We get
personally excited

00:48:03.060 --> 00:48:07.890
about a lot of different art,
but the gallery represents

00:48:07.890 --> 00:48:13.200
30 artists, and we're
really excited about them,

00:48:13.200 --> 00:48:14.890
and not all of them
are household names.

00:48:14.890 --> 00:48:16.610
As a matter of fact, few of
them are household names,

00:48:16.610 --> 00:48:17.443
but that's the goal.

00:48:17.443 --> 00:48:19.914
We're trying to make them
household names, because we

00:48:19.914 --> 00:48:22.080
feel strongly about them,
because we've vetted them,

00:48:22.080 --> 00:48:23.580
because we've been
to their studios,

00:48:23.580 --> 00:48:26.100
and we see how they paint,
because we understand

00:48:26.100 --> 00:48:27.060
what it means to them.

00:48:27.060 --> 00:48:29.117
It's not just painting
to make money.

00:48:29.117 --> 00:48:30.450
They're not producing a product.

00:48:30.450 --> 00:48:32.390
They're producing a
piece of themselves.

00:48:32.390 --> 00:48:33.090
It's important.

00:48:33.090 --> 00:48:35.400
They would do it even if
they didn't get paid for it.

00:48:35.400 --> 00:48:37.816
When it comes to putting those
artists in front of people,

00:48:37.816 --> 00:48:39.990
I don't ever get more
passionate than that.

00:48:39.990 --> 00:48:41.810
I really want people
to feel it, and it's

00:48:41.810 --> 00:48:44.690
got to start with
me as the dealer.

00:48:44.690 --> 00:48:47.610
But those artists still
need to be properly vetted.

00:48:47.610 --> 00:48:49.749
We need to understand
what it is they're doing

00:48:49.749 --> 00:48:50.790
and why they're doing it.

00:48:50.790 --> 00:48:53.440
It helps us equate value
to it and make sure

00:48:53.440 --> 00:48:54.790
that we set the market right.

00:48:54.790 --> 00:48:56.700
One of the things we
do with those artists

00:48:56.700 --> 00:48:59.870
is we help them
kind of life plan.

00:48:59.870 --> 00:49:01.540
I am coming to you today.

00:49:01.540 --> 00:49:03.430
I don't have a college degree.

00:49:03.430 --> 00:49:05.970
I learned what I
learned the hard way.

00:49:05.970 --> 00:49:11.080
I found my way into art in
the most oddest of paths.

00:49:11.080 --> 00:49:13.250
I come from two military people.

00:49:13.250 --> 00:49:15.550
My dad was in the Navy,
my mother in the Army.

00:49:15.550 --> 00:49:19.070
Their ideas about art, although
not their fault, were limited.

00:49:19.070 --> 00:49:24.587
And so I had to kind of
fight my way into it.

00:49:24.587 --> 00:49:26.670
There's a misperception
about us as gallery owners

00:49:26.670 --> 00:49:29.086
that we're silver spoon kids,
and that couldn't be further

00:49:29.086 --> 00:49:29.840
from the truth.

00:49:29.840 --> 00:49:30.750
Military family.

00:49:30.750 --> 00:49:33.601
Both of Amy's parents
are educators,

00:49:33.601 --> 00:49:37.680
and you know there's not a lot
of money in those occupations,

00:49:37.680 --> 00:49:42.900
but what we try to do
is go about what we

00:49:42.900 --> 00:49:46.950
can using two basic principles.

00:49:46.950 --> 00:49:51.421
Just hard work and--
I have a saying

00:49:51.421 --> 00:49:53.045
that I use and its
spend what you have.

00:49:53.045 --> 00:49:54.610
If you have time, spend time.

00:49:54.610 --> 00:49:56.110
If you have money, spend money.

00:49:56.110 --> 00:49:58.350
Well, in the beginning
we didn't have any money,

00:49:58.350 --> 00:49:59.150
so we spent time.

00:49:59.150 --> 00:50:00.274
We built all of our places.

00:50:00.274 --> 00:50:03.210
We have a little bit more
money now, so we invest in art.

00:50:03.210 --> 00:50:05.310
We'll buy a piece
every once in awhile,

00:50:05.310 --> 00:50:07.670
but-- and I'm deviating
a little bit--

00:50:07.670 --> 00:50:10.400
but the question specifically
was getting those new artists

00:50:10.400 --> 00:50:12.120
and getting them to
be household names.

00:50:12.120 --> 00:50:15.110
And in truth I'm hoping that all
of our artists can be that way,

00:50:15.110 --> 00:50:18.370
and I'm a big fan of putting
my stamp on them once I believe

00:50:18.370 --> 00:50:20.030
in them, but takes me awhile.

00:50:20.030 --> 00:50:22.836
And we've been wrong before,
if I'm being perfectly honest.

00:50:22.836 --> 00:50:24.210
We brought art in
that we thought

00:50:24.210 --> 00:50:26.460
was really, really
great only to find out

00:50:26.460 --> 00:50:28.280
the it was missing parts.

00:50:28.280 --> 00:50:30.390
There was something
wrong with it ultimately,

00:50:30.390 --> 00:50:34.670
whether it was a technical
aspect or a discrepancy

00:50:34.670 --> 00:50:36.380
just with the
artist's intentions.

00:50:36.380 --> 00:50:38.460
And we've let those
artists go very quickly.

00:50:38.460 --> 00:50:40.350
I have no problem
with cutting that tie,

00:50:40.350 --> 00:50:43.370
because I owe that
to our collectors.

00:50:43.370 --> 00:50:45.540
Round about kind
of wordy answer,

00:50:45.540 --> 00:50:47.387
but that's where we're
at with that one.

00:50:47.387 --> 00:50:49.470
CLIFF: Thank you very much
for speaking at Google.

00:50:49.470 --> 00:50:49.770
Thanks.

00:50:49.770 --> 00:50:50.520
ERIK HALL: Thanks.

00:50:50.520 --> 00:50:51.620
[APPLAUSE]

